            </div>
          </div>

          <h2 id="principal-residence">Principal Residence Requirement</h2>
          <p>This is the key restriction. <strong>Oshawa requires your STR to be your principal residence.</strong> You cannot operate a short-term rental from an investment property, second home, or any property where you don't actually live.</p>

          <div class="warning-box">
            <h4>Investment Properties Not Allowed</h4>
            <p>Unlike investor-friendly cities like Kingston or Sault Ste. Marie, Oshawa follows the same principal residence model as Toronto, Mississauga, and most GTA municipalities. If you own investment property in Oshawa, consider mid-term rentals (30+ days) which are exempt from STR rules.</p>
          </div>

          <h3>What Counts as Principal Residence?</h3>
          <p>Your principal residence is where you normally live, receive mail, file taxes from, and consider your permanent home. The city can verify this through:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Property tax records</li>
            <li>Driver's license address</li>
            <li>Utility bills</li>
            <li>Tax filings</li>
            <li>Other government documentation</li>
          </ul>

          <p>You cannot simply claim a property is your principal residence. The city has the authority to investigate and can revoke your license if they determine you've misrepresented residency.</p>

          <h2 id="license-requirements">License Requirements</h2>
          <p>You must obtain a valid STR license before advertising or operating any short-term rental in Oshawa. Here's what you need:</p>

          <h3>License Fees</h3>
          <div class="fee-breakdown">
            <div class="fee-item">
              <span class="fee-label">Application fee</span>
              <span class="fee-amount">$50</span>
            </div>
            <div class="fee-item">
              <span class="fee-label">License fee</span>
              <span class="fee-amount">$100</span>
            </div>
            <div class="fee-item total">
              <span class="fee-label">Total</span>
              <span class="fee-amount">$150</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>Application Requirements</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Floor plan</strong> showing exits, windows, rooms, and common areas (hand-drawn is acceptable)</li>
            <li><strong>Proof of insurance</strong> with minimum $2,000,000 liability coverage that explicitly identifies STR use</li>
            <li><strong>Local contact information</strong> for someone available 24/7 who can respond within one hour</li>
            <li><strong>Declaration</strong> attesting compliance with zoning, safety requirements, and property owner consent</li>
            <li><strong>Condo board approval</strong> if applicable (must confirm STR use is permitted)</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="callout">
            <div class="callout-icon">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
                <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
                <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="callout-content">
              <strong>Inspection required:</strong> All STR properties must pass an inspection by City Licensing Inspectors before your license is approved. This is scheduled during the application process.
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>Insurance Requirements</h3>
          <p>Your insurance policy must meet specific criteria:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Minimum <strong>$2,000,000 liability coverage</strong> per occurrence</li>
            <li>Policy must <strong>explicitly identify STR use</strong></li>
            <li>You must provide <strong>15 days written notice</strong> to the city if insurance is cancelled</li>
            <li>Standard homeowner's insurance typically doesn't cover STR activity</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="night-limits">Night Limits</h2>
          <p>Oshawa imposes two restrictions on how you can rent:</p>

          <div class="comparison-table">
