              <div class="comparison-col">Restriction</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Limit</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Per booking</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">28 consecutive days max</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Per year</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">180 days total</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>The 180-night annual limit matches Toronto's regulations. Once you hit 180 nights in a calendar year, you cannot accept additional short-term bookings until the next year.</p>

          <div class="success-box">
            <h4>Tracking Your Nights</h4>
            <p>Keep accurate records of every booking. Most platforms provide annual summaries, but maintain your own spreadsheet as backup. The city can request these records at any time.</p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="room-rentals">Room Rental Rules</h2>
          <p>If you want to rent individual rooms while remaining in your home, Oshawa has specific restrictions:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Maximum 2 rooms</strong> can be rented at a time</li>
            <li><strong>Maximum 2 occupants per room</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Cannot operate both</strong> whole-home and room rentals simultaneously</li>
            <li>No other rental use permitted in the same dwelling unit</li>
          </ul>

          <p>Room rentals still count toward your 180-night annual limit. Each night a room is rented is one night of your allocation.</p>

          <h2 id="safety-requirements">Safety Requirements</h2>
          <p>Your STR must meet specific safety standards:</p>

          <h3>Mandatory Safety Equipment</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Working smoke alarms</strong> on each level of the dwelling</li>
            <li><strong>Carbon monoxide detectors</strong> on all sleeping levels</li>
            <li><strong>Posted emergency instructions</strong> clearly visible to guests</li>
            <li><strong>Visitor's Code</strong> provided to all renters before or at check-in</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Visitor's Code</h3>
          <p>You must provide every guest with a Visitor's Code that outlines:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Property rules and expectations</li>
            <li>Emergency contact information</li>
            <li>Relevant city bylaws (noise, parking, garbage)</li>
            <li>Check-out procedures</li>
          </ul>

          <p>Keep confirmation that each renter received the Visitor's Code for your records.</p>

          <h2 id="mat-tax">Municipal Accommodation Tax (MAT)</h2>
          <p>Oshawa implemented a 5% Municipal Accommodation Tax effective October 1, 2024. This applies to all transient accommodations including short-term rentals.</p>

          <div class="key-stats" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);">
            <div class="stat-item highlight">
              <span class="stat-value">5%</span>
              <span class="stat-label">MAT rate</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat-item">
              <span class="stat-value">Quarterly</span>
              <span class="stat-label">Remittance schedule</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>MAT Requirements</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Collect 5%</strong> of the purchase price from guests</li>
            <li><strong>Remit quarterly</strong> to the City Treasurer</li>
            <li><strong>Display as separate line item</strong> on receipts/invoices as "Municipal Accommodation Tax"</li>
            <li><strong>Keep records for 7 years</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "A Provider identified as a bed and breakfast or short-term rental shall remit the amount of the M.A.T. collected for the previous three months and submit the quarterly statements on or before the last day every calendar quarter end."
            <cite>City of Oshawa By-law 93-2020, Section 9.2</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <div class="callout">
